    <h2 style="font-size:2rem; margin-top:1rem; color:#002f5f;">Accelerating the Sustainable Development Goals through Open Collaboration</h2>
    <p style="font-size:1.125rem; margin-top:0.5rem;">
      The <strong>Open for SDG Conference</strong> brings together United Nations leaders,
      open‑source communities and innovators from across the globe to explore how open
      technologies can advance the 2030 Agenda. This site provides an overview of the
      conference objectives, sessions and key participants.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:3rem;">
    <h3 style="font-size:1.75rem; color:#002f5f; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">About the UN Office for Digital & Emerging Technologies (ODET)</h3>
    <p>
      As of 1&nbsp;January&nbsp;2025 the United Nations transitioned the Envoy on Technology into the
      <strong>Office for Digital and Emerging Technologies (ODET)</strong>.  The new office holds a
      strengthened mandate to help the UN address the rapidly evolving technological landscape
      and to support implementation of the <em>Global Digital Compact</em>【731529764474628†L51-L75】.  ODET
      champions an inclusive, multistakeholder approach to digital governance rooted in the
      UN Charter, human rights and the sustainable development agenda【731529764474628†L63-L75】.  Its mission
      spans five strategic areas: advocating for digital cooperation, facilitating
      multistakeholder dialogues, advising UN leadership on technology trends, strengthening
      coordination across the UN system, and supporting follow‑up of the Global Digital
      Compact【731529764474628†L68-L75】.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:3rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:1.5rem;">
    <div style="flex:1 1 300px;">
      <h3 style="font-size:1.75rem; color:#002f5f; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Open Source &amp; the Sustainable Development Goals</h3>
      <p>
        Achieving the 17 Sustainable Development Goals requires scalable, affordable and
        inclusive digital solutions.  Open‑source projects – ranging from software and
        data sets to artificial intelligence models, standards and content – form the
        backbone of what the UN calls <em>digital public goods</em>.  These shared resources
        unlock innovation and equity by allowing anyone to build upon and localize
        proven technologies.  The Office for Digital and Emerging Technologies notes that
        investing in open‑source software, open data, open AI models, open standards and
        open content is key to achieving the SDGs【628719890919091†L50-L59】.  All such digital public
        goods must adhere to privacy and ethical standards, do no harm and remain
        accessible to all【628719890919091†L55-L59】.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div style="flex:1 1 300px; text-align:center;">
      <img src="/images/sdg.png" alt="The 17 Sustainable Development Goals" style="max-width:100%; height:auto; border-radius:8px;" />
      <small style="display:block; margin-top:0.5rem; color:#666;">The 17 Sustainable Development Goals</small>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:3rem;">
    <h3 style="font-size:1.75rem; color:#002f5f; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Introducing GOSIM</h3>
    <p>
      The <strong>Global Open‑Source Innovation Meetup (GOSIM)</strong> is a volunteer‑driven
      platform dedicated to nurturing grassroots open‑source projects.  Born from the
      collective vision of a global open‑source community, GOSIM provides a stage where
      projects can shine, collaborate and evolve【246078012704320†L18-L30】.  It subscribes to
      an open, diverse and inclusive culture【246078012704320†L24-L34】 and operates on three
      pillars: an annual <em>GOSIM Conference</em> that dives into technology trends and
      best practices, hands‑on <em>GOSIM Workshops</em> for hackathons and competitions,
      and a year‑round <em>GOSIM Spotlight</em> program that supports promising projects
      through sponsorships and grants【246078012704320†L38-L56】.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom:3rem;">
    <h3 style="font-size:1.75rem; color:#002f5f; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Conference Format &amp; Topics</h3>
    <p>The Open for SDG Conference is structured around thematic sessions that explore how open‑source technologies can accelerate progress toward specific sustainable development goals:</p>
    <ul style="list-style:square inside; margin-left:1rem;">
      <li><strong>Open Data for the UN SDGs</strong> – sharing case studies on public healthcare data and brainstorming an open data initiative.</li>
      <li><strong>Open Policy for the UN SDGs</strong> – discussing governance models, contribution pathways and policy considerations for UN engagement with open‑source projects.</li>
      <li><strong>Open Science for the UN SDGs</strong> – highlighting open science principles, barriers, enablers and ethical considerations for collaborative research.</li>
      <li><strong>Future AI for the UN SDGs</strong> – envisioning inclusive, responsible AI futures and exploring how advanced AI can serve sustainable development.</li>
      <li><strong>Show &amp; Tell</strong> – spotlighting practical use cases and open‑source projects supporting the UN SDGs.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Each theme features a short keynote followed by a moderated panel discussion with experts from academia, industry and international organizations.  Please see the <a href="/agenda">Agenda</a> for timings and speaker details.</p>
  </section>

